he campaign.\n\nNow on to the cons... Every mission you run is of a certain type, Cruiser Clash, Assassination, Breakthrough, Convoy, Data Retrieval, etc... A lot of my decisions about where to deploy were based entirely on what type of mission it was. Some of the mission types just aren't fun, imo. If I had to defend a convoy, I wouldn't run it. I'd do Assassination missions but I didn't like doing them if I was the attacker. Likewise for Data Retrieval [though I don't recall being the defender on that ever].\n\nThe reason for this is, partly because the enemy AI cheats, and partly because of how those missions are handled. I'll get back to the enemy AI cheating in a moment, but for the Assassination and Data Retrieval missions, you have to destroy a vessel, or run a boarding action on it to get the data before it warps out. You have about 3-ish minutes to do this before the warping out ability is off of cooldown. The enemy ships will spend the entire time running from you, which, okay, fair enough. You can also force an enemy's warp out to be aborted by performing a boarding action, which IF IT SUCCEEDS, will cancel their warp and put it on a brief cooldown. These missions are doable, but they're frustrating because you end up spending the whole mission rushing towards the enemy ship just so that you can get there in time to be in range to MAYBE succeed in cancelling their warp out.\n\nAs for the enemy AI cheating? Aside from them always knowing where you are, even though they shouldn't, there's fleet limits. Each mission you can field a fleet of 300-700 points-worth of ships. So for a 300 point mission you could bring 2 Light Cruisers, and 2 escort vessels. Or a Light Cruiser, and 5-6 escort vessels. There's other various combinations you could bring, but the cheapest non-escort vessel you can bring is the Dauntless Light Cruiser at 105 points each. Ships get more expensive as you move up the tiers. The point is, because the cheapest non-escort vessel you can bring is 105 points, on a 300-point mission you can only bring 2. But the enemy - who should be on the same points-limit as you - will bring 3 Light Cruisers, and some escort ships. Or some other combination of ships whose points exceed the limit. I'm not referring to missions where it's stated you're fighting a superior force, or you're aiding an ally. I'm referring to missions where it's explicitly stated that you should be on equal footing with the enemy's forces.\n\nAnd finally, the cost of the DLC factions seems a bit high to me. It's not as bad as the DLC factions for say... Blood Bowl 2 [whose faction DLCs are technically cheaper, but there's more of them], but I dunno. They seem a little pricey. My opinion here might be coloured somewhat by there being Space Marines ships already in the base game, though of course you can't play them. This point is, more than the other points I've made here, pretty subjective.\n\nI know this 'review' seems overly negative, but really, it's easy to focus on the negatives, since they'll stick out at you more than a good thing. I'm still clicking the \"recommend\" button, because I *did* enjoy this game. Quite a bit, actually. And I'm looking forward to playing around with Elite Mode whatever that is, and the other factions, and maybe even replaying the campaign.", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1505516033, "written_during_early_access": false, "timestamp_updated": 1505516033, "recommendationid": "34983010", "language": "english", "votes_down": 0, "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.502594", "voted_up": true}, {"author": {"last_played": 1500663344, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0, "num_reviews": 6, "playtime_forever": 31, "steamid": "76561198105220909", "num_games_owned": 53}, "votes_funny": 0, "votes_up": 1, "comment_count": 0, "review": "Great game, quite fun to setup, micro-managing to the max if you wish to.\n\nMy only issue is that people with a low-end pc wont be able to experience as miuch fun, 